    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-20T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-20T23:00:00-05:00" n="447"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d447">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 EW/12–2144: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Certain
                            <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Representatives</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="91" xml:id="d447fn91">The diplomatic representatives at London, Paris,
                        Madrid, Lisbon, Bern, Cairo, Ankara, and Stockholm.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-21T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 21, 1944—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Barnes understands that all members of Muraviev Cabinet except Muraviev himself
                    and Dimov have been released but have signed pledges to appear before the
                    Peoples courts when called. This move is generally considered to mean that only
                    Dimov is in danger. It is generally believed that the Russians had been
                    persuaded not to take action against the other ministers since such action would
                    undermine the declaration of war against Germany which constituted the final
                    action of the Cabinet in question. War criminal trials will begin on December 21
                    and there is some fear that the penalties will be heavy and justice may not be
                    dispensed impartially. Those persons bearing the greatest responsibility for
                    Bulgarian participation in the war such as Filov, Gabrovsky<note n="92"
                        xml:id="d447fn92">Peter Gabrovski, Bulgarian Minister of Interior, February
                        1940—August 1943.</note> and Prince Cyril are now imprisoned in Russia where
                    they will be held for trial by an international court.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
